-- SQL Day 12 - HAVING

-- Count employees in each department
SELECT department, COUNT(*)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department;

-- Departments having more than 1 employee
SELECT department, COUNT(*)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;

-- Average salary greater than 35000
SELECT department, AVG(salary)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department
HAVING AVG(salary) > 35000;

-- Maximum salary greater than 38000
SELECT department, MAX(salary)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department
HAVING MAX(salary) > 38000;

# SQL Day 12 - HAVING

## 📘 Definition

HAVING is used to filter groups after they are created using GROUP BY.

---

## 🔹 Syntax

```sql
SELECT column_name, AGGREGATE_FUNCTION(column_name)
FROM table_name
GROUP BY column_name
HAVING AGGREGATE_FUNCTION(column_name) condition;
```

---

## 🔹 Difference Between WHERE and HAVING

| WHERE | HAVING |
|--------|---------|
| Filters rows | Filters groups |
| Executes before GROUP BY | Executes after GROUP BY |
| Cannot use aggregate functions | Can use aggregate functions |

---

## 🔹 Examples

### Departments with more than one employee

```sql
SELECT department, COUNT(*)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;
```

### Departments with average salary greater than 35000

```sql
SELECT department, AVG(salary)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department
HAVING AVG(salary) > 35000;
```

---

## 🎤 Interview Questions

### What is HAVING?

HAVING filters grouped data after GROUP BY.

### Why can't WHERE use COUNT() or AVG()?

Because WHERE executes before GROUP BY, while aggregate functions are calculated after grouping.

### Difference between WHERE and HAVING?

WHERE filters rows, while HAVING filters groups.

---

## 📝 Key Points

- HAVING is usually used with GROUP BY.
- HAVING can use aggregate functions like COUNT(), AVG(), SUM(), MIN(), and MAX().
- WHERE cannot use aggregate functions directly.

